The paper discusses model compression techniques for deep neural networks, specifically weight pruning, and focuses on optimizing for real-time execution on mobile devices. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) or machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper introduces a new sparsity dimension, which could potentially fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) or neural networks (cs.NE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the use of a compiler-assisted DNN inference framework, which could be relevant to the computer architecture (cs.AR) sub-category.
